    "oe": [
     {
      "jaar": 2023,
      "tijdvak": 1,
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2023 Tijdvak 1 Woordenschat & Grammatica (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "Fill-in context:\n\n\"If the government __ (introduce) stricter pollution laws ten years ago, the air quality __ (be) much better today. Many scientists agree that the delay __ (cost) the environment dearly.\"",
      "v": "(a) Fill in the correct verb forms for the three gaps using the correct conditional or tense.\n(b) What type of conditional is used in the first sentence? Justify your answer.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) had introduced / would be / has cost. (b) Mixed conditional: type 3 in the if-clause (past perfect → unreal past action) + type 2 in the main clause (would + bare infinitive → unreal present result). \"If the government had introduced…, the air quality would be better today.\""
     },
     {
      "jaar": 2024,
      "tijdvak": 2,
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2024 Tijdvak 2 Woordenschat (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "Read the sentence and answer the questions:\n\n\"The renewable energy sector has grown exponentially over the past decade, with solar panels becoming increasingly affordable for ordinary households.\"",
      "v": "(a) What does \"exponentially\" mean in this context? Use context clues.\n(b) Identify one collocation in the sentence and explain what it means.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) \"Exponentially\" = growing at a very fast, accelerating rate. Context clue: \"has grown… over the past decade\" combined with \"increasingly affordable\" suggests rapid, sustained growth.\n(b) \"Renewable energy\" (fixed combination = energy from natural sources like sun/wind); or \"ordinary households\" (typical homes); or \"increasingly affordable\" (gradually becoming cheaper). A collocation is a pair of words that naturally go together."
     },
     {
      "jaar": 2022,
      "tijdvak": 1,
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2022 Tijdvak 1 Grammatica (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "A student wrote: \"Yesterday I have visited the new museum in town. It was very interesting and I have learned a lot about local history.\"",
      "v": "(a) Find two grammatical errors in the student's writing and correct them.\n(b) Explain the rule that applies.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) \"I have visited\" → \"I visited\" (yesterday = finished past time marker → simple past). \"I have learned\" → \"I learned\" (same reason). (b) Present perfect is used for experiences without a specific time OR for actions with present relevance. When a finished past time expression is present (yesterday, last year, in 2020), simple past must be used."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "\"Scientists announced yesterday that they have discovered a new species of deep-sea fish. The creature, which lives at depths of over 3,000 metres, was found by researchers who had been studying the Pacific Ocean for two years. They say the discovery could change our understanding of marine biology.\"",
      "v": "(a) Rewrite the first sentence in reported speech, beginning with: \"Scientists announced that…\"\n(b) Identify the tense shift that occurs when converting direct speech to reported speech and explain why it happens.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) Scientists announced that they had discovered a new species of deep-sea fish. (b) Present perfect (\"have discovered\") shifts to past perfect (\"had discovered\") in reported speech. This backshift happens because reported speech moves the time frame one step back — what was present at the time of speaking becomes past from the reporter's perspective."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "\"Every year, millions of plastic bottles are thrown away by consumers. These bottles are collected by waste management companies, sorted by workers in recycling plants, and eventually melted down and turned into new products.\"",
      "v": "(a) Underline all passive constructions in the text.\n(b) Why does the writer use the passive voice throughout this passage? Give two reasons.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) \"are thrown away\" / \"are collected\" / \"sorted\" (elliptical passive) / \"melted down\" / \"turned into\". (b) 1. The focus is on what happens to the bottles, not on who does the action — the agent (consumers, companies, workers) is less important than the process. 2. The passive creates an impersonal, objective tone appropriate for informational writing about environmental processes."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "\"The prefix 'un-' means not, as in 'unhappy' or 'unclear'. The suffix '-tion' turns a verb into a noun, as in 'pollution' (pollute + tion) or 'education' (educate + tion). Understanding word formation helps you decode unknown vocabulary.\"",
      "v": "(a) Using the information in the text, form the noun from the verb \"communicate\" and the adjective \"predictable\".\n(b) What strategy does the writer recommend for dealing with unknown words? Is this useful? Explain.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) communicate + -tion → communication. un- + predictable → unpredictable (adjective with negative prefix). (b) The writer recommends using knowledge of prefixes and suffixes to decode unknown vocabulary. Useful: it helps guess meaning without a dictionary, especially in reading and listening tests where you cannot stop. Limitation: not all words follow regular patterns (e.g. \"information\" ≠ \"inform + ation\" in a predictable way for every learner)."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "\"Climate scientists warn that unless drastic action is taken in the next decade, global temperatures will rise by more than 2°C above pre-industrial levels. If this threshold had been reached in 2015, the consequences would already have been irreversible.\"",
      "v": "(a) Identify the type of conditional used in each sentence.\n(b) Rewrite the second sentence as a first conditional, keeping the same meaning as closely as possible.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) Sentence 1: Type 1 conditional (unless + present simple → will + bare infinitive): real possibility in the future. Sentence 2: Type 3 conditional (if + past perfect → would have + past participle): imaginary situation in the past. (b) First conditional equivalent: \"If this threshold is reached before 2035, the consequences will become irreversible.\" (Note: exact wording varies; must use if + present simple → will + bare infinitive.)"
     }
    ],
